@acidjazz `flutter upgrade` does not change your Flutter projects, it only updates your Flutter installation. 

Specifically, once a `Podfile` exists in your Flutter project, Flutter tooling does not attempt to overwrite it, as you may have custom settings in there. As you note, this is unfortunate, because the `Podfile` was likely written by an earlier version of Flutter tooling using a template that does not work with newer CocoaPods versions and/or with Swift projects.

We are working on a project template with a clearer separation of the files Flutter tooling create and depend on (specifically, for plugins) and those that the app author is supposed to own.

